# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: curl-http-tool
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:curl-http-tool/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] The software was first released in 1996, originally named `httpget` and then became `urlget`, before adopting the current name of `curl`.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] The original author and lead developer is the Swedish developer Daniel Stenberg, who created curl to power part of an IRC bot, because he wanted to automatically provide currency exchange rates, fetched from a website, to users in an IRC chat room.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] `libcurl` is a client-side URL transfer library that powers `curl`.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] It supports numerous internet protocols including DICT, FILE, FTP, FTPS, GOPHER, GOPHERS, HTTP, HTTPS, IMAP, IMAPS, LDAP, LDAPS, MQTT, POP3, POP3S, RTMP, RTMPS, RTSP, SCP, SFTP, SMB, SMBS, SMTP, SMTPS, TELNET, TFTP, WS and WSS.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] libcurl supports HTTP versions 0.9, 1.0, 1.1, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 including h2c, prior-knowledge, dual-connect modes, and QUIC with 0-RTT handshakes.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] It also offers proxy and networking support, including SOCKS4, SOCKS5, HAProxy, and HTTP proxies with chaining and Unix domain sockets, as well as user-plus-password authentication.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] Advanced name-resolution features include DNS-over-HTTPS, custom DNS servers, host/port mappings, and DNS caching.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] Additional functionality includes file transfer resume, FTP uploading, form-based HTTP upload, HTTPS certificates, and mechanisms for controlling and monitoring transfers such as configurable timeouts, automatic retries, rate limiting, and detection of stalled connections.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] The library also provides enhanced reporting features, including JSON-formatted metadata, content-disposition handling, IDN hostname display, and customizable transfer information.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] The `libcurl` library is thread-safe and IPv6 compatible.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] Bindings are available for more than 50 languages, including C, C++, Java, Julia (is bundled with), PHP and Python.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] The `libcurl` library supports SSL/TLS through GnuTLS, mbedTLS, SChannel (on Windows), OpenSSL, BoringSSL, AWS-LC, QuicTLS, LibreSSL, AmiSSL, wolfSSL and rustls.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] `curl` is a command-line tool for getting or sending data, including files, using URL syntax.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] `curl` provides an interface to the `libcurl` library; it supports every protocol `libcurl` supports.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] `curl` supports HTTPS, and performs SSL or TLS certificate verification by default.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] When `curl` connects to a remote server via HTTPS, it will obtain the remote server certificate, then checks against its CA certificate store the validity of the remote server to ensure the remote server is the one it claims to be.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] Some `curl` packages are bundled with a CA certificate store file.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] There are several options to specify a CA certificate, such as `--cacert` and `--capath`.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] The `--cacert` option can be used to specify the location of the CA certificate store file.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] Starting with Windows 10 version 1809, Windows ships with `curl.exe`.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] `curl` will return an error message if the remote server is using a self-signed certificate, or if the remote server certificate is not signed by a CA listed in the CA cert file.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] `-k` or `--insecure` option can be used to skip certificate verification.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] Alternatively, if the remote server is trusted, the remote server CA certificate can be added to the CA certificate store file.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] `tiny-curl` is a lightweight version of libcurl developed by wolfSSL Inc. for embedded and resource-constrained devices.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] It implements HTTPS functionality in roughly 100 KB of code on typical 32-bit architectures.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] curl and libcurl are distributed under the MIT License. tiny-curl, a version of curl optimized for embedded systems and supported by wolfSSL, is available under both the GNU GPLv3-or-later and commercial licensing.
[src:curl-http-tool/curl] Rock-solid curl, the long-term support (LTS) edition, uses the same curl license by default, with an option for commercial licensing for organizations that require contractual support or warranty coverage.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This document assumes that you are familiar with HTML and general networking.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The increasing amount of applications moving to the web has made "HTTP Scripting" more frequently requested and wanted.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] To be able to automatically extract information from the web, to fake users, to post or upload data to web servers are all important tasks today.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl is a command line tool for doing all sorts of URL manipulations and transfers, but this particular document focuses on how to use it when doing HTTP requests for fun and profit.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This documents assumes that you know how to invoke `curl --help` or `curl --manual` to get basic information about it.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl is not written to do everything for you.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It makes the requests, it gets the data, it sends data and it retrieves the information.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You probably need to glue everything together using some kind of script language or repeated manual invokes.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] HTTP is the protocol used to fetch data from web servers.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It is a simple protocol that is built upon TCP/IP.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The protocol also allows information to get sent to the server from the client using a few different methods, as is shown here.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] HTTP is plain ASCII text lines being sent by the client to a server to request a particular action, and then the server replies a few text lines before the actual requested content is sent to the client.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The client, curl, sends an HTTP request.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The request contains a method (like GET, POST, HEAD etc), a number of request headers and sometimes a request body.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The HTTP server responds with a status line (indicating if things went well), response headers and most often also a response body.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The "body" part is the plain data you requested, like the actual HTML or the image etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Using curl's option `--verbose` (`-v` as a short option) displays what kind of commands curl sends to the server, as well as a few other informational texts.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] `--verbose` is the single most useful option when it comes to debug or even understand the curl<->server interaction.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Sometimes even `--verbose` is not enough.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Then `--trace` and `--trace-ascii` offer even more details as they show **everything** curl sends and receives.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Many times you may wonder what exactly is taking all the time, or you want to know the amount of milliseconds between two points in a transfer.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] For those, and other similar situations, the `--trace-time` option is what you need.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] When doing parallel transfers, it is relevant to see which transfer is doing what.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] When response headers are received (and logged) you need to know which transfer these are for.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] By default curl sends the response to stdout.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You need to redirect it somewhere to avoid that, most often that is done with `-o` or `-O`.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The Uniform Resource Locator format is how you specify the address of a particular resource on the Internet.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You know these, you have seen URLs like https://curl.se/ or https://example.com/ a million times.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The formal name is not URL, it is **URI**.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The hostname is usually resolved using DNS or your /etc/hosts file to an IP address and that is what curl communicates with.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Alternatively you specify the IP address directly in the URL instead of a name.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Each protocol curl supports operates on a default port number, be it over TCP or in some cases UDP.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Normally you do not have to take that into consideration, but at times you run test servers on other ports or similar.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Then you can specify the port number in the URL with a colon and a number immediately following the hostname.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The port number you specify in the URL is the number that the server uses to offer its services.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Sometimes you may use a proxy, and then you may need to specify that proxy's port number separately from what curl needs to connect to the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Some services are setup to require HTTP authentication and then you need to provide name and password which is then transferred to the remote site in various ways depending on the exact authentication protocol used.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You need to pay attention that this kind of HTTP authentication is not what is usually done and requested by user-oriented websites these days.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] They tend to use forms and cookies instead.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The path part is sent off to the server to request that it sends back the associated response.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The path is what is to the right side of the slash that follows the hostname and possibly port number.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The simplest and most common request/operation made using HTTP is to GET a URL.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The URL could itself refer to a webpage, an image or a file.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The client issues a GET request to the server and receives the document it asked for.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] you get a webpage returned in your terminal window.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The entire HTML document this URL identifies.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] All HTTP replies contain a set of response headers that are normally hidden, use curl's `--include` (`-i`) option to display them as well as the rest of the document.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You can ask the remote server for ONLY the headers by using the `--head` (`-I`) option which makes curl issue a HEAD request.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] In some special cases servers deny the HEAD method while others still work, which is a particular kind of annoyance.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The HEAD method is defined and made so that the server returns the headers exactly the way it would do for a GET, but without a body.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It means that you may see a `Content-Length:` in the response headers, but there must not be an actual body in the HEAD response.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] A single curl command line may involve one or many URLs.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The most common case is probably to use one, but you can specify any amount of URLs.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You then get requests repeated over and over for all the given URLs.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If you use `--data` to POST to the URL, using multiple URLs means that you send that same POST to all the given URLs.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Sometimes you need to operate on several URLs in a single command line and do different HTTP methods on each.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] For this, you might enjoy the `--next` option.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It is a separator that separates a bunch of options from the next.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] All the URLs before `--next` get the same method and get all the POST data merged into one.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] When curl reaches the `--next` on the command line, it resets the method and the POST data and allow a new set.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Perhaps this is best shown with a few examples.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Forms are the general way a website can present an HTML page with fields for the user to enter data in, and then press some kind of 'OK' or 'Submit' button to get that data sent to the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The server then typically uses the posted data to decide how to act.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Like using the entered words to search in a database, or to add the info in a bug tracking system, display the entered address on a map or using the info as a login-prompt verifying that the user is allowed to see what it is about to see.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Of course there has to be some kind of program on the server end to receive the data you send.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You cannot invent something out of the air.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] In your favorite browser, this form appears with a text box to fill in and a press-button labeled "OK".
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If you fill in '1905' and press the OK button, your browser then creates a new URL to get for you.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The URL gets `junk.cgi?birthyear=1905&press=OK` appended to the path part of the previous URL.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If the original form was seen on the page `www.example.com/when/birth.html`, the second page you get becomes `www.example.com/when/junk.cgi?birthyear=1905&press=OK`.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The GET method makes all input field names get displayed in the URL field of your browser.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] That is generally a good thing when you want to be able to bookmark that page with your given data, but it is an obvious disadvantage if you entered secret information in one of the fields or if there are a large amount of fields creating a long and unreadable URL.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The HTTP protocol then offers the POST method.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This way the client sends the data separated from the URL and thus you do not see any of it in the URL address field.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This kind of POST uses the Content-Type `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` and is the most widely used POST kind.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The data you send to the server MUST already be properly encoded, curl does not do that for you.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] For example, if you want the data to contain a space, you need to replace that space with `%20`, etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Failing to comply with this most likely causes your data to be received wrongly and messed up.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If you repeat `--data` several times on the command line, curl concatenates all the given data pieces - and put a `&` symbol between each data segment.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Back in late 1995 they defined an additional way to post data over HTTP.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It is documented in the RFC 1867, why this method sometimes is referred to as RFC 1867-posting.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This method is mainly designed to better support file uploads.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This clearly shows that the Content-Type about to be sent is `multipart/form-data`.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] A common way for HTML based applications to pass state information between pages is to add hidden fields to the forms.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Hidden fields are already filled in, they are not displayed to the user and they get passed along as all the other fields.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] To POST this with curl, you do not have to think about if the fields are hidden or not.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] When you are about to fill in a form and send it to a server by using curl instead of a browser, you are of course interested in sending a POST exactly the way your browser does.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] An easy way to get to see this, is to save the HTML page with the form on your local disk, modify the 'method' to a GET, and press the submit button (you could also change the action URL if you want to).
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You then clearly see the data get appended to the URL, separated with a `?`-letter as GET forms are supposed to.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Perhaps the best way to upload data to an HTTP server is to use PUT.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Then again, this of course requires that someone put a program or script on the server end that knows how to receive an HTTP PUT stream.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] HTTP Authentication is the ability to tell the server your username and password so that it can verify that you are allowed to do the request you are doing.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The Basic authentication used in HTTP (which is the type curl uses by default) is **plain text** based, which means it sends username and password only slightly obfuscated, but still fully readable by anyone that sniffs on the network between you and the remote server.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The site might require a different authentication method (check the headers returned by the server), and then `--ntlm`, `--digest`, `--negotiate` or even `--anyauth` might be options that suit you.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Sometimes your HTTP access is only available through the use of an HTTP proxy.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This seems to be especially common at various companies.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] An HTTP proxy may require its own user and password to allow the client to get through to the Internet.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If your proxy requires the authentication to be done using the NTLM method, use `--proxy-ntlm`, if it requires Digest use `--proxy-digest`.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If you use any one of these user+password options but leave out the password part, curl prompts for the password interactively.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Do note that when a program is run, its parameters might be possible to see when listing the running processes of the system.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Thus, other users may be able to watch your passwords if you pass them as plain command line options.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It is worth noting that while this is how HTTP Authentication works, many websites do not use this concept when they provide logins etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] See the Web Login chapter further below for more details on that.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] An HTTP request may include a 'referer' field (yes it is misspelled), which can be used to tell from which URL the client got to this particular resource.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Some programs/scripts check the referer field of requests to verify that this was not arriving from an external site or an unknown page.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] While this is a stupid way to check something so easily forged, many scripts still do it.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Using curl, you can put anything you want in the referer-field and thus more easily be able to fool the server into serving your request.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Similar to the referer field, all HTTP requests may set the User-Agent field.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It names what user agent (client) that is being used.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Many applications use this information to decide how to display pages.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Silly web programmers try to make different pages for users of different browsers to make them look the best possible for their particular browsers.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] They usually also do different kinds of JavaScript etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] At times, you may learn that getting a page with curl does not return the same page that you see when getting the page with your browser.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Then you know it is time to set the User Agent field to fool the server into thinking you are one of those browsers.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] By default, curl uses curl/VERSION, such as User-Agent: curl/8.11.0.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] When a resource is requested from a server, the reply from the server may include a hint about where the browser should go next to find this page, or a new page keeping newly generated output.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The header that tells the browser to redirect is `Location:`.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl does not follow `Location:` headers by default, but displays such pages in the same manner it displays all HTTP replies.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It does however feature an option that makes it attempt to follow the `Location:` pointers.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If you use curl to POST to a site that immediately redirects you to another page, you can safely use `--location` (`-L`) and `--data`/`--form` together. curl only uses POST in the first request, and then revert to GET in the following operations.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Browsers typically support at least two other ways of redirects that curl does not: first the html may contain a meta refresh tag that asks the browser to load a specific URL after a set number of seconds, or it may use JavaScript to do it.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The way the web browsers do "client side state control" is by using cookies.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Cookies are names with associated contents.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The cookies are sent to the client by the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The server tells the client for what path and hostname it wants the cookie sent back, and it also sends an expiration date and a few more properties.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] When a client communicates with a server with a name and path as previously specified in a received cookie, the client sends back the cookies and their contents to the server, unless of course they are expired.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Many applications and servers use this method to connect a series of requests into a single logical session.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] To be able to use curl in such occasions, we must be able to record and send back cookies the way the web application expects them.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Cookies are sent as common HTTP headers.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This is practical as it allows curl to record cookies by recording headers.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl has a full blown cookie parsing engine built-in that comes in use if you want to reconnect to a server and use cookies that were stored from a previous connection (or hand-crafted manually to fool the server into believing you had a previous connection).
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl's "cookie engine" gets enabled when you use the `--cookie` option.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If you only want curl to understand received cookies, use `--cookie` with a file that does not exist.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl has the ability to read and write cookie files that use the same file format that Netscape and Mozilla once used.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It is a convenient way to share cookies between scripts or invokes.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] There are a few ways to do secure HTTP transfers.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] By far the most common protocol for doing this is what is generally known as HTTPS, HTTP over SSL.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] SSL encrypts all the data that is sent and received over the network and thus makes it harder for attackers to spy on sensitive information.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] SSL (or TLS as the current version of the standard is called) offers a set of advanced features to do secure transfers over HTTP.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl supports encrypted fetches when built to use a TLS library and it can be built to use one out of a fairly large set of libraries - `curl -V` shows which one your curl was built to use (if any).
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] In the HTTPS world, you use certificates to validate that you are the one you claim to be, as an addition to normal passwords. curl supports client- side certificates.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] All certificates are locked with a passphrase, which you need to enter before the certificate can be used by curl.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] The passphrase can be specified on the command line or if not, entered interactively when curl queries for it.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl also tries to verify that the server is who it claims to be, by verifying the server's certificate against a locally stored CA cert bundle.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Failing the verification causes curl to deny the connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You must then use `--insecure` (`-k`) in case you want to tell curl to ignore that the server cannot be verified.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] More about server certificate verification and CA cert bundles can be read in the `SSLCERTS` document.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Doing fancy stuff, you may need to add or change elements of a single curl request.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] You can delete a default header by providing one without content.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It should be noted that curl selects which methods to use on its own depending on what action to ask for.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] `-d` makes a POST, `-I` makes a HEAD and so on.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] If you use the `--request` / `-X` option you can change the method keyword curl selects, but you do not modify curl's behavior.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] This means that if you for example use -d "data" to do a POST, you can modify the method to a `PROPFIND` with `-X` and curl still thinks it sends a POST.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] curl however still acts as if it sent a GET so it does not send any request body etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] While not strictly HTTP related, it still causes a lot of people problems so here's the executive run-down of how the vast majority of all login forms work and how to login to them using curl.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] It can also be noted that to do this properly in an automated fashion, you most certainly need to script things and do multiple curl invokes etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] First, servers mostly use cookies to track the logged-in status of the client, so you need to capture the cookies you receive in the responses.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Then, many sites also set a special cookie on the login page (to make sure you got there through their login page) so you should make a habit of first getting the login-form page to capture the cookies set there.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Some web-based login systems feature various amounts of JavaScript, and sometimes they use such code to set or modify cookie contents.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Possibly they do that to prevent programmed logins, like this manual describes how to...
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Anyway, if reading the code is not enough to let you repeat the behavior manually, capturing the HTTP requests done by your browsers and analyzing the sent cookies is usually a working method to work out how to shortcut the JavaScript need.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] In the actual `<form>` tag for the login, lots of sites fill-in random/session or otherwise secretly generated hidden tags and you may need to first capture the HTML code for the login form and extract all the hidden fields to be able to do a proper login POST.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Remember that the contents need to be URL encoded when sent in a normal POST.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] Many times when you run curl on a site, you notice that the site does not seem to respond the same way to your curl requests as it does to your browser's.
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] A good helper to make sure you do this right, is the web browsers' developers tools that let you view all headers you send and receive (even when using HTTPS).
[src:curl-http-tool/httpscripting] A more raw approach is to capture the HTTP traffic on the network with tools such as Wireshark or tcpdump and check what headers that were sent and received by the browser.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:curl-http-tool/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl is a tool for transferring data from or to a server using URLs.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] It supports these protocols: DICT, FILE, FTP, FTPS, GOPHER, GOPHERS, HTTP, HTTPS, IMAP, IMAPS, LDAP, LDAPS, MQTT, MQTTS, POP3, POP3S, RTSP, SCP, SFTP, SMB, SMBS, SMTP, SMTPS, TELNET, TFTP, WS and WSS.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl is powered by libcurl for all transfer-related features.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] You can find a detailed description in RFC 3986.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If you provide a URL without a leading "protocol://" scheme, curl guesses what protocol you want.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] It then defaults to HTTP but assumes others based on often-used hostname prefixes.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] For example, for hostnames starting with "ftp." curl assumes you want FTP.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] You can specify any amount of URLs on the command line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] They are fetched in a sequential manner in the specified order unless you use --parallel.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] You can specify command line options and URLs mixed and in any order on the command line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl attempts to reuse connections when doing multiple transfers, so that getting many files from the same server does not use multiple connects and setup handshakes.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Connection reuse can only be done for URLs specified for a single command line invocation and cannot be performed between separate curl runs.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Everything provided on the command line that is not a command line option or its argument, curl assumes is a URL and treats it as such.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] You can specify multiple URLs or parts of URLs by writing lists within braces or ranges within brackets.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] When using [] or {} sequences when invoked from a command line prompt, you probably have to put the full URL within double quotes to avoid the shell from interfering with it.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] This also goes for other characters treated special, like for example '&', '?' and '*'.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] The separate globbing components can be referenced in the --output option to allow pieces to be reused in the target filename.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Starting in curl 8.21.0, the separate globbing parts can be named and referenced by their names.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] The case sensitive alphanumeric name is set enclosed within angle brackets after the opening character.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Setting the same glob name twice is an error.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl supports command line variables (added in 8.3.0).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Set variables with --variable name=content or --variable name@file (where "file" can be stdin if set to a single dash (-)).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Variable contents can be expanded in option parameters using "{{name}}" if the option name is prefixed with "--expand-".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] This gets the contents of the variable "name" inserted, or a blank if the name does not exist as a variable.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Insert "{{" verbatim in the string by prefixing it with a backslash, like "\{{".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] You can access and expand environment variables by importing them with "--variable %name".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] This imports the variable called "name" but exits with an error if that environment variable is not already set.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] To provide a default value in case it is not already set, use "--variable %name=content" or "--variable %name@content".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] When expanding variables, curl supports a set of functions that can make the variable contents more convenient to use.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] It can trim leading and trailing white space with "trim", output the contents as a JSON quoted string with "json", URL encode the string with "url", base64 encode it with "b64" and base64 decode it with "64dec".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] To apply functions to a variable expansion, add them colon separated to the right side of the variable.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Variable content holding null bytes that are not encoded when expanded causes an error.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Example: get the contents of a file called $HOME/.secret into a variable called "fix".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Command line variables and expansions were added in 8.3.0.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If not told otherwise, curl writes the received data to stdout.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] It can be instructed to instead save that data into a local file, using the --output or --remote-name options.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If curl is given multiple URLs to transfer on the command line, it similarly needs multiple options for where to save them.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl does not parse or otherwise "understand" the content it gets or writes as output.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] It does no encoding or decoding, unless explicitly asked to with dedicated command line options.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl supports numerous protocols, or put in URL terms: schemes.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Your particular build may not support them all.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Lets you lookup words using online dictionaries.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Read or write local files. curl does not support accessing "file://" URL remotely, but when running on Microsoft Windows using the native UNC approach works.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl supports the File Transfer Protocol with a lot of tweaks and levers.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl supports HTTP with numerous options and variations.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] It can speak HTTP version 0.9, 1.0, 1.1, 2 and 3 depending on build options and the correct command line options.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Using the mail reading protocol, curl can download emails for you.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl can do directory lookups for you, with or without TLS.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Downloading over MQTT equals subscribing to a topic while uploading/posting equals publishing on a topic.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Downloading from a pop3 server means getting an email.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl supports SSH version 2 scp transfers.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl supports SFTP (draft 5) done over SSH version 2.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl supports SMB version 1 for upload and download.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Uploading contents to an SMTP server means sending an email.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Fetching a telnet URL starts an interactive session where it sends what it reads on stdin and outputs what the server sends it.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl normally displays a progress meter during operations, indicating the amount of transferred data, transfer speeds and estimated time left, etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] The progress meter displays the transfer rate in bytes per second.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] The used suffixes ("k" for kilo, "M" for mega, "G" for giga, "T" for tera, "P" for peta and "E" for exa) are 1024 based.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Strictly speaking this makes the units kibibyte and mebibyte etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl displays this data to the terminal by default, so if you invoke curl to do an operation and it is about to write data to the terminal, it disables the progress meter as otherwise it would mess up the output mixing progress meter and response data.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If you want a progress meter for HTTP POST or PUT requests, you need to redirect the response output to a file, using shell redirect (>), --output or similar.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] This does not apply to FTP upload as that operation does not spit out any response data to the terminal.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If you prefer a progress bar instead of the regular meter, --progress-bar is your friend.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] You can also disable the progress meter completely with the --silent option.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If you use a later version, chances are this man page does not fully document it.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If you use an earlier version, this document tries to include version information about which specific version that introduced changes.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Many of the options require an additional value next to them.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If provided text does not start with a dash, it is presumed to be and treated as a URL.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] The short "single-dash" form of the options, -d for example, may be used with or without a space between it and its value, although a space is a recommended separator.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] The long double-dash form, --data for example, requires a space between it and its value.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Short version options that do not need any additional values can be used immediately next to each other, like for example you can specify all the options -O, -L and -v at once as -OLv.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] In general, all boolean options are enabled with --option and yet again disabled with --no-option.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] That is, you use the same option name but prefix it with "no-".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] In this list we mostly show the --option version of them.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] When --next is used, it resets the parser state and you start again with a clean option state, except for the options that are global.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Global options retain their values and meaning even after --next.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] If the long option name ends with an equals sign ("="), the argument is the text following on its right side.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] The first argument that is exactly two dashes ("--"), marks the end of options; any argument after the end of options is interpreted as a URL argument even if it starts with a dash.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] curl does little to no verification of the contents of command line arguments.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] Passing in "creative octets" like newlines might trigger unexpected results.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p01] The following options are global: --fail-early, --libcurl, --parallel-immediate, --parallel-max-host, --parallel-max, --parallel, --progress-bar, --rate, --show-error, --stderr, --styled-output, --trace-ascii, --trace-config, --trace-ids, --trace-time, --trace and --verbose.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Connect to the server through an abstract Unix domain socket, instead of using the network.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Note: netstat shows the path of an abstract socket prefixed with "@", however the <path> argument should not have this leading character.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --abstract-unix-socket is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the filename points to an existing alt-svc cache file, that gets used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] After a completed transfer, the cache is saved to the filename again if it has been modified.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Specify a "" filename (zero length) to avoid loading/saving and make curl handle the cache in memory.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] You may want to restrict your umask to prevent other users on the same system to access the created file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If this option is used several times, curl loads contents from all the files but the last one is used for saving.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Figure out authentication method automatically, and use the most secure one the remote site claims to support.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is done by first doing a request and checking the response-headers, thus possibly inducing an extra network round-trip.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is used instead of setting a specific authentication method, which you can do with --basic, --digest, --ntlm, and --negotiate.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Using --anyauth is not recommended if you do uploads from stdin, since it may require data to be sent twice and then the client must be able to rewind.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the need should arise when uploading from stdin, the upload operation fails.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --proxy-anyauth, --basic and --digest.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP SFTP) When used in an upload, this option makes curl append to the target file instead of overwriting it.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the remote file does not exist, it is created.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Note that this flag is ignored by some SFTP servers (including OpenSSH).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --append multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Use AWS V4 signature authentication in the transfer.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The provider argument is a string that is used by the algorithm when creating outgoing authentication headers.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The region argument is a string that points to a geographic area of a resources collection (region-code) when the region name is omitted from the endpoint.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The service argument is a string that points to a function provided by a cloud (service-code) when the service name is omitted from the endpoint.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --aws-sigv4 is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Use HTTP Basic authentication with the remote host.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This method is the default and this option is usually pointless, unless you use it to override a previously set option that sets a different authentication method (such as --ntlm, --digest, or --negotiate).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --basic multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Use the operating system's native CA store for certificate verification.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is independent of other CA certificate locations set at run time or build time.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Those locations are searched in addition to the native CA store.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option works with OpenSSL and its forks (BoringSSL, LibreSSL, etc) on Windows (Added in 7.71.0) and on Apple OS when libcurl is built with Apple SecTrust enabled.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option works with wolfSSL on Windows, Linux (Debian, Ubuntu, Gentoo, Fedora, RHEL), macOS, Android and iOS.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option works with GnuTLS (Added in 8.5.0) and also uses Apple SecTrust when libcurl is built with it.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option works with Rustls on Windows, macOS, Android and iOS.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] On Linux it is equivalent to using the Mozilla CA certificate bundle.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When used with Rustls _only_ the native CA store is consulted, not other locations set at run time or build time.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option currently has no effect for Schannel.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is the native TLS library from Microsoft, that by default uses the native CA store for verification unless overridden by a CA certificate location setting.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --ca-native multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --cacert, --capath, --dump-ca-embed, --insecure and --proxy-ca-native.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Use the specified certificate file to verify the peer.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The file may contain multiple CA certificates.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The certificate(s) must be in PEM format.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Normally curl is built to use a default file for this, so this option is typically used to alter that default file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] curl recognizes the environment variable named 'CURL_CA_BUNDLE' if it is set and the TLS backend is not Schannel, and uses the given path as a path to a CA cert bundle.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (Windows) curl automatically looks for a CA certs file named 'curl-ca-bundle.crt', either in the same directory as curl.exe, or in the Current Working Directory, or in any folder along your PATH.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] curl 8.11.0 added a build-time option to disable this search behavior, and another option to restrict search to the application's directory.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (Schannel) This option is supported for Schannel in Windows 7 or later (added in 7.60.0).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is supported for backward compatibility with other SSL engines; instead it is recommended to use Windows' store of root certificates (the default for Schannel).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --cacert is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --capath, --dump-ca-embed and --insecure.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Use the specified certificate directory to verify the peer.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If curl is built against OpenSSL, multiple paths can be provided by separating them with the appropriate platform-specific separator (e.g.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] "path1:path2:path3" on Unix-style platforms for "path1;path2;path3" on Windows).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The certificates must be in PEM format, and if curl is built against OpenSSL, the directory must have been processed using the c_rehash utility supplied with OpenSSL.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Using --capath can allow OpenSSL-powered curl to make SSL-connections much more efficiently than using --cacert if the --cacert file contains many CA certificates.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If this option is set, the default capath value is ignored.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --capath is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --cacert, --dump-ca-embed and --insecure.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Use the specified client certificate file when getting a file with HTTPS, FTPS or another SSL-based protocol.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the optional password is not specified, it is queried for on the terminal.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Note that this option assumes a certificate file that is the private key and the client certificate concatenated.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See --cert and --key to specify them independently.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] In the <certificate> portion of the argument, you must escape the character ":" as "\:" so that it is not recognized as the password delimiter.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Similarly, you must escape the double quote character as \" so that it is not recognized as an escape character.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If curl is built against OpenSSL, and the engine pkcs11 or pkcs11 provider is available, then a PKCS#11 URI (RFC 7512) can be used to specify a certificate located in a PKCS#11 device.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] A string beginning with "pkcs11:" is interpreted as a PKCS#11 URI.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If a PKCS#11 URI is provided, then the --engine option is set as "pkcs11" if none was provided and the --cert-type option is set as "ENG" or "PROV" if none was provided (depending on OpenSSL version).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If curl is built against GnuTLS, a PKCS#11 URI can be used to specify a certificate located in a PKCS#11 device.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (Schannel) Client certificates must be specified by a path expression to a certificate store.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (Loading PFX is not supported; you can import it to a store first).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] You can use "<store location>\<store name>\<thumbprint>" to refer to a certificate in the system certificates store, for example, "CurrentUser\MY\934a7ac6f8a5d579285a74fa61e19f23ddfe8d7a".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Thumbprint is usually a SHA-1 hex string which you can see in certificate details.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Following store locations are supported: CurrentUser, LocalMachine, CurrentService, Services, CurrentUserGroupPolicy, LocalMachineGroupPolicy and LocalMachineEnterprise.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --cert is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --cert-type, --key and --key-type.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Verify the status of the server certificate by using the Certificate Status Request (aka.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If this option is enabled and the server sends an invalid (e.g. expired) response, if the response suggests that the server certificate has been revoked, or no response at all is received, the verification fails.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This support is currently only implemented in the OpenSSL and GnuTLS backends.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --cert-status multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Set type of the provided client certificate.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] PEM, DER, ENG, PROV and P12 are recognized types.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The default type depends on the TLS backend and is usually PEM.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --cert is a pkcs11: URI then ENG or PROV is the default type (depending on OpenSSL version).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --cert-type is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Specify which cipher suites to use in the connection if it negotiates TLS 1.2 (1.1, 1.0).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The list of ciphers suites must specify valid ciphers.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --ciphers is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --tls13-ciphers, --proxy-ciphers and --curves.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Request a compressed response using one of the algorithms curl supports, and automatically decompress the content.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Response headers are not modified when saved, so if they are "interpreted" separately again at a later point they might appear to be saying that the content is (still) compressed; while in fact it has already been decompressed.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If this option is used and the server sends an unsupported encoding, curl reports an error.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is a request, not an order; the server may or may not deliver data compressed.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] WARNING: when decompressing data, even tiny transfers might be expanded and generate a huge amount of bytes.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] You might want to limit using this option to only known and trusted sites using secure protocols, perhaps in combination with --max-filesize.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --compressed multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is a request, not an order; the server may or may not do it.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This allows the data to be sent compressed over the wire, and automatically decompressed in the receiving end, to save bandwidth.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --compressed-ssh multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-compressed-ssh.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Specify a text file to read curl arguments from.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The command line arguments found in the text file are used as if they were provided on the command line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Options and their parameters must be specified on the same line in the file, separated by whitespace, colon, or the equals sign.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Long option names can optionally be given in the config file without the initial double dashes and if so, the colon or equals characters can be used as separators.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the option is specified with one or two dashes, there can be no colon or equals character between the option and its parameter.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the parameter contains whitespace or starts with a colon (:) or equals sign (=), it must be specified enclosed within double quotes ("like this").
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Within double quotes the following escape sequences are available: \ \", \t, \n, \r and \v.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] A backslash preceding any other letter is ignored.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the first non-blank column of a config line is a '#' character, that line is treated as a comment.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Only write one option per physical line in the config file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] A single line is required to be no more than 10 megabytes (since 8.2.0).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Specify the filename to --config as minus "-" to make curl read the file from stdin.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Note that to be able to specify a URL in the config file, you need to specify it using the --url option, and not by writing the URL on its own line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When curl is invoked, it (unless --disable is used) checks for a default config file and uses it if found, even when --config is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] 8) On Windows, if it finds no .curlrc file in the sequence described above, it checks for one in the same directory the curl executable is placed.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] On Windows two filenames are checked per location: .curlrc and _curlrc, preferring the former.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Older versions on Windows checked for _curlrc only.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Maximum time in seconds that you allow curl's connection to take.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This only limits the connection phase, so if curl connects within the given period it continues - if not it exits.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The decimal value needs to be provided using a dot (.) as decimal separator - not the local version even if it might be using another separator.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The connection phase is considered complete when the DNS lookup and requested TCP, TLS or QUIC handshakes are done.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --connect-timeout is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] For a request intended for the "HOST1:PORT1" pair, connect to "HOST2:PORT2" instead.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is only used to establish the network connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] It does NOT affect the hostname/port number that is used for TLS/SSL (e.g.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] SNI, certificate verification) or for the application protocols.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] "HOST1" and "PORT1" may be empty strings, meaning any host or any port number.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] "HOST2" and "PORT2" may also be empty strings, meaning use the request's original hostname and port number.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] A hostname specified to this option is compared as a string, so it needs to match the name used in the request URL.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] It can be either numerical such as "127.0.0.1" or the full hostname such as "example.org".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Resume a previous transfer from the given byte offset.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The given offset is the exact number of bytes that are skipped, counting from the beginning of the source file before it is transferred to the destination.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If used with uploads, the FTP server command SIZE is not used by curl.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Use "-C -" to instruct curl to automatically find out where/how to resume the transfer.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] It then uses the given output/input files to figure that out.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When using this option for HTTP uploads using POST or PUT, functionality is not guaranteed.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The HTTP protocol has no standard interoperable resume upload and curl uses a set of headers for this purpose that once proved working for some servers and have been left for those who find that useful.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This command line option is mutually exclusive with --range: you can only use one of them for a single transfer.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The --no-clobber and --remove-on-error options cannot be used together with --continue-at.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --continue-at is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) This option has two slightly separate cookie sending functions.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Either: pass the exact data to send to the HTTP server in the Cookie header.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] It is supposedly data previously received from the server in a "Set-Cookie:" line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The data should be in the format "NAME1=VALUE1; NAME2=VALUE2".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When given a set of specific cookies, curl populates its cookie header with this content explicitly in all outgoing request(s).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If multiple requests are done due to authentication, followed redirects or similar, they all get this cookie header passed on.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Or: If no "=" symbol is used in the argument, it is instead treated as a filename to read previously stored cookie from.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option also activates the cookie engine which makes curl record incoming cookies, which may be handy if you are using this in combination with the --location option or do multiple URL transfers on the same invoke.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the filename is a single minus ("-"), curl reads the contents from stdin.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the filename is an empty string ("") and is the only cookie input, curl activates the cookie engine without any cookies.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The file format of the file to read cookies from should be plain HTTP headers (Set-Cookie style) or the Netscape/Mozilla cookie file format.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The file specified with --cookie is only used as input.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] To store cookies, use the --cookie-jar option.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If you use the Set-Cookie file format and do not specify a domain then the cookie is not sent since the domain never matches.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] To address this, set a domain in Set-Cookie line (doing that includes subdomains) or preferably: use the Netscape format.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Users often want to both read cookies from a file and write updated cookies back to a file, so using both --cookie and --cookie-jar in the same command line is common. curl ignores filenames specified with --cookie which do not exist or point to a directory.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If curl is built with PSL (Public Suffix List) support, it detects and discards cookies that are specified for such suffix domains that should not be allowed to have cookies.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If curl is not built with PSL support, it has no ability to stop super cookies.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --cookie-jar and --junk-session-cookies.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Specify to which file you want curl to write all cookies after a completed operation. curl writes all cookies from its in-memory cookie storage to the given file at the end of operations.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Even if no cookies are known, a file is created so that it removes any formerly existing cookies from the file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The file uses the Netscape cookie file format.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If you set the filename to a single minus, "-", the cookies are written to stdout.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The file specified with --cookie-jar is only used for output.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] To read cookies, use the --cookie option.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This command line option activates the cookie engine that makes curl record and use cookies.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the cookie jar cannot be created or written to, the whole curl operation does not fail or even report an error clearly.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Using --verbose gets a warning displayed, but that is the only visible feedback you get about this possibly lethal situation.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --cookie-jar is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --cookie and --junk-session-cookies.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When used in conjunction with the --output option, curl creates the necessary local directory hierarchy as needed.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option creates the directories mentioned with the --output option combined with the path possibly set with --output-dir.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the combined output filename uses no directory, or if the directories it mentions already exist, no directories are created.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Created directories are made with mode 0750 on Unix-style file systems.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] To create remote directories when using FTP or SFTP, try --ftp-create-dirs.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --create-dirs multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --ftp-create-dirs and --output-dir.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (SFTP SCP FILE) When curl is used to create files remotely using one of the supported protocols, this option allows the user to set which 'mode' to set on the file at creation time, instead of the default 0644.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option takes an octal number as argument.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --create-file-mode is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP SMTP) Convert line feeds to carriage return plus line feeds in upload.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --crlf multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Provide a file using PEM format with a Certificate Revocation List that may specify peer certificates that are to be considered revoked.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --crlfile is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Set specific curves to use during SSL session establishment according to RFC 8422, 5.1.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Multiple algorithms can be provided by separating them with ":" (e.g.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The parameter is available identically in the OpenSSL "s_client" and "s_server" utilities.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If this option is set, the default curves list built into OpenSSL are ignored.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --curves is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP MQTT) Send the specified data in a POST request to the HTTP server, in the same way that a browser does when a user has filled in an HTML form and presses the submit button.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option makes curl pass the data to the server using the content-type application/x-www-form-urlencoded.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If any of these options is used more than once on the same command line, the data pieces specified are merged with a separating &-symbol.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Thus, using '-d name=daniel -d skill=lousy' would generate a post chunk that looks like 'name=daniel&skill=lousy'.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If you start the data with the letter @, the rest should be a filename to read the data from, or - if you want curl to read the data from stdin.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Posting data from a file named 'foobar' would thus be done with --data @foobar.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When --data is told to read from a file like that, carriage returns, newlines and null bytes are stripped out.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If you do not want the @ character to have a special interpretation use --data-raw instead.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The data for this option is passed on to the server exactly as provided on the command line. curl does not convert, change or improve it.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] It is up to the user to provide the data in the correct form.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is mutually exclusive with --form, --head and --upload-file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --data-binary, --data-urlencode and --data-raw.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) This option is an alias for --data.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --data-binary, --data-raw and --data-urlencode.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Post data exactly as specified with no extra processing whatsoever.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If you start the data with the letter @, the rest should be a filename.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] "@-" makes curl read the data from stdin.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Data is posted in a similar manner as --data does, except that newlines and carriage returns are preserved and conversions are never done.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Like --data the default content-type sent to the server is application/x-www-form-urlencoded.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If you want the data to be treated as arbitrary binary data by the server then set the content-type to octet-stream: -H "Content-Type: application/octet-stream".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If this option is used several times, the ones following the first append data as described in --data.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Post data similarly to --data but without the special interpretation of the @ character.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Post data, similar to the other --data options with the exception that this performs URL-encoding.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] To be CGI-compliant, the <data> part should begin with a name followed by a separator and a content specification.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] URL-encode the content and pass that on.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Be careful so that the content does not contain any "=" or "@" symbols, as that makes the syntax match one of the other cases below.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The preceding "=" symbol is not included in the data.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] URL-encode the content part and pass that on.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Note that the name part is expected to be URL-encoded already.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] load data from the given file (including any newlines), URL-encode that data and pass it on in the POST.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Using "@-" makes curl read the data from stdin.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The name part gets an equal sign appended, resulting in name=urlencoded-file-content.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Note that the name is expected to be URL-encoded already.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (GSS/kerberos) Set LEVEL what curl is allowed to delegate when it comes to user credentials.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Delegates if and only if the OK-AS-DELEGATE flag is set in the Kerberos service ticket, which is a matter of realm policy.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Unconditionally allow the server to delegate.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --delegation is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Enable HTTP Digest authentication.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This authentication scheme avoids sending the password over the wire in clear text.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Use this in combination with the normal --user option to set username and password.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --digest multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --user, --proxy-digest and --anyauth.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If used as the first parameter on the command line, the curlrc config file is not read or used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See the --config for details on the default config file search path.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --disable multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Disable the use of the EPRT and LPRT commands when doing active FTP transfers. curl normally first attempts to use EPRT before using PORT, but with this option, it uses PORT right away.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] EPRT is an extension to the original FTP protocol, and does not work on all servers, but enables more functionality in a better way than the traditional PORT command.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the server is accessed using IPv6, this option has no effect as EPRT is necessary then.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disabling EPRT only changes the active behavior.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If you want to switch to passive mode you need to not use --ftp-port or force it with --ftp-pasv.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --disable-eprt multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-disable-eprt.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Disable the use of the EPSV command when doing passive FTP transfers. curl normally first attempts to use EPSV before PASV, but with this option, it does not try EPSV.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If the server is an IPv6 host, this option has no effect as EPSV is necessary then.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disabling EPSV only changes the passive behavior.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If you want to switch to active mode you need to use --ftp-port.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --disable-epsv multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-disable-epsv.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Exit with error if passed a URL containing a username.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Probably most useful when the URL is being provided at runtime or similar.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Accepting and using credentials in a URL is normally considered a security hazard as they are easily leaked that way.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --disallow-username-in-url multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-disallow-username-in-url.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (DNS) Send outgoing DNS requests through the given interface.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is a counterpart to --interface (which does not affect DNS).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The supplied string must be an interface name (not an address).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --dns-interface is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] For --dns-interface to work, it requires that the underlying libcurl is built to support c-ares.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --dns-ipv4-addr and --dns-ipv6-addr.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (DNS) Bind to a specific IP address when making IPv4 DNS requests, so that the DNS requests originate from this address.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The argument should be a single IPv4 address.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --dns-ipv4-addr is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] For --dns-ipv4-addr to work, it requires that the underlying libcurl is built to support c-ares.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --dns-interface and --dns-ipv6-addr.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (DNS) Bind to a specific IP address when making IPv6 DNS requests, so that the DNS requests originate from this address.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The argument should be a single IPv6 address.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --dns-ipv6-addr is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] For --dns-ipv6-addr to work, it requires that the underlying libcurl is built to support c-ares.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --dns-interface and --dns-ipv4-addr.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (DNS) Set the list of DNS servers to be used instead of the system default.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The list of IP addresses should be separated with commas.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Port numbers may also optionally be given, appended to the IP address separated with a colon.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --dns-servers is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] For --dns-servers to work, it requires that the underlying libcurl is built to support c-ares.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (DNS) Same as --cert-status but used for DoH (DNS-over-HTTPS).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Verify the status of the DoH servers' certificate by using the Certificate Status Request (aka.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If this option is enabled and the DoH server sends an invalid (e.g. expired) response, if the response suggests that the server certificate has been revoked, or no response at all is received, the verification fails.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --doh-cert-status multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-doh-cert-status.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (DNS) By default, every connection curl makes to a DoH server is verified to be secure before the transfer takes place.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option tells curl to skip the verification step and proceed without checking.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] WARNING: using this option makes the DoH transfer and name resolution insecure.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is equivalent to --insecure and --proxy-insecure but used for DoH (DNS-over-HTTPS) only.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --doh-insecure multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-doh-insecure.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --doh-url, --insecure and --proxy-insecure.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (DNS) Specify which DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH) server to use to resolve hostnames, instead of using the default name resolver mechanism.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Some SSL options that you set for your transfer also apply to DoH since the name lookups take place over SSL.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The certificate verification settings are not inherited but are controlled separately via --doh-insecure and --doh-cert-status.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] By default, DoH is bypassed when initially looking up DNS records of the DoH server.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] You can specify the IP address(es) of the DoH server with --resolve to avoid this.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is unset if an empty string "" is used as the URL.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --doh-url is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Write the CA bundle embedded in curl to standard output, then quit.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If curl was not built with a default CA bundle embedded, the output is empty.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --dump-ca-embed multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-dump-ca-embed.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --ca-native, --cacert, --capath, --proxy-ca-native, --proxy-cacert and --proxy-capath.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP FTP) Write the received protocol headers to the specified file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If no headers are received, the use of this option creates an empty file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Specify "-" as filename (a single minus) to have it written to stdout.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Starting in curl 8.10.0, specify "%" (a single percent sign) as filename writes the output to stderr.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When used in FTP, the FTP server response lines are considered being "headers" and thus are saved there.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Starting in curl 8.11.0, using the --create-dirs option can also create missing directory components for the path provided in --dump-header.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Having multiple transfers in one set of operations (i.e. the URLs in one --next clause), appends them to the same file, separated by a blank line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --dump-header is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTPS) Specify how to do ECH (Encrypted Client Hello).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Attempt ECH if possible, but do not fail if ECH is not attempted.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Attempt ECH and fail if that is not possible.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] ECH only works with TLS 1.3 and also requires using DoH or providing an ECHConfigList on the command line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] A base64 encoded ECHConfigList that is used for ECH.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Most ECH related errors cause error CURLE_ECH_REQUIRED (101).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --ech is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Deprecated option (added in 7.84.0).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Prior to that it only had an effect on curl if built to use old versions of OpenSSL.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Specify the path name to the Entropy Gathering Daemon socket.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The socket is used to seed the random engine for SSL connections.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --egd-file is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) Select the OpenSSL crypto engine to use for cipher operations.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Use "--engine list" to print a list of build-time supported engines.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Note that not all (and possibly none) of the engines may be available at runtime.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The OpenSSL concept "engines" has been superseded by "providers" in OpenSSL 3, and this option should work fine to specify such as well.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --engine is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Make a conditional HTTP request for the specific ETag read from the given file by sending a custom If-None-Match header using the stored ETag.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] For correct results, make sure that the specified file contains only a single line with the desired ETag.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] A non-existing or empty file is treated as an empty ETag.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Use the option --etag-save to first save the ETag from a response, and then use this option to compare against the saved ETag in a subsequent request.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --etag-compare is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Save an HTTP ETag to the specified file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] An ETag is a caching related header, usually returned in a response.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If no ETag is sent by the server, an empty file is created.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] In many situations you want to use an existing etag in the request to avoid downloading the same resource again but also save the new etag if it has indeed changed, by using both etag options --etag-save and --etag-compare with the same filename, in the same command line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Starting in curl 8.12.0, using the --create-dirs option can also create missing directory components for the path provided in --etag-save.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --etag-save is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Maximum time in seconds that you allow curl to wait for a 100-continue response when curl emits an Expects: 100-continue header in its request.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When curl stops waiting, it continues as if a response was received.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The decimal value needs to be provided using a dot (".") as decimal separator - not the local version even if it might be using another separator.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --expect100-timeout is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Fail with error code 22 and with no response body output at all for HTTP transfers returning HTTP response codes at 400 or greater.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] In normal cases when an HTTP server fails to deliver a document, it returns a body of text stating so (which often also describes why and more) and a 4xx HTTP response code.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This command line option prevents curl from outputting that data and instead returns error 22 early.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] By default, curl does not consider HTTP response codes to indicate failure.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] To get both the error code and also save the content, use --fail-with-body instead.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This method is not fail-safe and there are occasions where non-successful response codes slip through, especially when authentication is involved (response codes 401 and 407).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --fail multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is mutually exclusive with --fail-with-body.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --fail-with-body and --fail-early.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Fail and exit on the first detected transfer error.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When curl is used to do multiple transfers on the command line, it attempts to operate on each given URL, one by one.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] By default, it ignores errors if there are more URLs given and the last URL's success determines the error code curl returns.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Early failures are "hidden" by subsequent successful transfers.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Using this option, curl instead returns an error on the first transfer that fails, independent of the amount of URLs that are given on the command line.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This way, no transfer failures go undetected by scripts and similar.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option does not imply --fail, which causes transfers to fail due to the server's HTTP status code.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] You can combine the two options, however note --fail is not global and is therefore contained by --next.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is global and does not need to be specified for each use of --next.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --fail-early multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Return an error on server errors where the HTTP response code is 400 or greater).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] In normal cases when an HTTP server fails to deliver a document, it returns an HTML document stating so (which often also describes why and more).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option allows curl to output and save that content but also to return error 22.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is an alternative option to --fail which makes curl fail for the same circumstances but without saving the content.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --fail-with-body multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-fail-with-body.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is mutually exclusive with --fail.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (TLS) No TLS backend currently supports this feature.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Use false start during the TLS handshake.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] False start is a mode where a TLS client starts sending application data before verifying the server's Finished message, thus saving a round trip when performing a full handshake.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --false-start multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) Instructs curl to follow HTTP redirects and to do the custom request method set with --request when following redirects as the HTTP specification says.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The method string set with --request is used in subsequent requests for the status codes 307 or 308, but may be reset to GET for 301, 302 and 303.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is subtly different than --location, as that option always sets the custom method in all subsequent requests independent of response code.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Restrict which protocols a redirect is accepted to follow with --proto-redir.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When --netrc is used in combination with this option, credentials for the followed-to hosts may also be selected from that file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --follow multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --request, --location, --proto-redir and --max-redirs.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP SMTP IMAP) For the HTTP protocol family, emulate a filled-in form in which a user has pressed the submit button.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This makes curl POST data using the Content-Type multipart/form-data according to RFC 2388.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] For SMTP and IMAP protocols, this composes a multipart mail message to transmit.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This enables uploading of binary files etc.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] To force the 'content' part to be a file, prefix the filename with an @ sign.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] To get the content part from a file, prefix the filename with the symbol <.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The difference between @ and < is then that @ makes a file get attached in the post as a file upload, while the < makes a text field and gets the contents for that text field from a file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Read content from stdin instead of a file by using a single "-" as filename.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When stdin is used, the contents is buffered in memory first by curl to determine its size and allow a possible resend.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Defining a part's data from a named non-regular file (such as a named pipe or similar) is not subject to buffering and is instead read at transmission time; since the full size is unknown before the transfer starts, such data is sent as chunks by HTTP and rejected by IMAP.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Example: send your essay in a text field to the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Note that if a filename/path is quoted by double-quotes, any double-quote or backslash within the filename must be escaped by backslash.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The headers= keyword may appear more than once and above notes about quoting apply.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When headers are read from a file, empty lines and lines starting with '#' are ignored; each header can be folded by splitting between two words and starting the continuation line with a space; embedded carriage-returns and trailing spaces are stripped.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Example: the following command sends an SMTP mime email consisting in an inline part in two alternative formats: plain text and HTML.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Data can be encoded for transfer using encoder=.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is mutually exclusive with --data, --head and --upload-file.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] See also --data, --form-string and --form-escape.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP IMAP SMTP) Pass on names of multipart form fields and files using backslash-escaping instead of percent-encoding.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --form-escape is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP SMTP IMAP) Similar to --form except that the value string for the named parameter is used literally.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Leading @ and < characters, and the ";type=" string in the value have no special meaning.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Use this in preference to --form if there is any possibility that the string value may accidentally trigger the @ or < features of --form.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) When an FTP server asks for "account data" after username and password has been provided, this data is sent off using the ACCT command.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --ftp-account is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) If authenticating with the USER and PASS commands fails, send this command.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] When connecting to Tumbleweed's Secure Transport server over FTPS using a client certificate, using "SITE AUTH" tells the server to retrieve the username from the certificate.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --ftp-alternative-to-user is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP SFTP) When an FTP or SFTP URL/operation uses a path that does not currently exist on the server, the standard behavior of curl is to fail.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Using this option, curl instead attempts to create missing directories.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --ftp-create-dirs multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-ftp-create-dirs.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Control what method curl should use to reach a file on an FTP(S) server.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Do a single CWD operation for each path part in the given URL.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] For deep hierarchies this means many commands.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is how RFC 1738 says it should be done.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is the default but the slowest behavior.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Do no CWD at all. curl does SIZE, RETR, STOR etc and gives the full path to the server for each of these commands.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Do one CWD with the full target directory and then operate on the file "normally" (like in the multicwd case).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This is somewhat more standards compliant than "nocwd" but without the full penalty of "multicwd".
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --ftp-method is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Use passive mode for the data connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Passive is the internal default behavior, but using this option can be used to override a previous --ftp-port option.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Reversing an enforced passive really is not doable but you must then instead enforce the correct --ftp-port again.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Passive mode means that curl tries the EPSV command first and then PASV, unless --disable-epsv is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --ftp-pasv multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is mutually exclusive with --ftp-port.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Reverse the default initiator/listener roles when connecting with FTP.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] make curl pick the same IP address that is already used for the control connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable the use of PORT with --ftp-pasv.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable the attempt to use the EPRT command instead of PORT by using --disable-eprt.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] You can also append ":[start]-[end]" to the right of the address, to tell curl what TCP port range to use.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] That means you specify a port range, from a lower to a higher number.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] A single number works as well, but do note that it increases the risk of failure since the port may not be available.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] If --ftp-port is provided several times, the last set value is used.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Send a PRET command before PASV (and EPSV).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Certain FTP servers, mainly drftpd, require this non-standard command for directory listings as well as up and downloads in PASV mode.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --ftp-pret multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Do not use the IP address the server suggests in its response to curl's PASV command when curl connects the data connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Instead curl reuses the same IP address it already uses for the control connection.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option is enabled by default (added in 7.74.0).
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This option has no effect if PORT, EPRT or EPSV is used instead of PASV.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --ftp-skip-pasv-ip multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-ftp-skip-pasv-ip.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Use CCC (Clear Command Channel) Shuts down the SSL/TLS layer after authenticating.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The rest of the control channel communication is unencrypted.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] This allows NAT routers to follow the FTP transaction.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --ftp-ssl-ccc multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The passive mode does not initiate the shutdown, but instead waits for the server to do it, and does not reply to the shutdown from the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] The active mode initiates the shutdown and waits for a reply from the server.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --ftp-ssl-ccc-mode multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-ftp-ssl-ccc-mode.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (FTP) Require SSL/TLS for the FTP login, clear for transfer.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Allows secure authentication, but non-encrypted data transfers for efficiency.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Fails the transfer if the server does not support SSL/TLS.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Providing --ftp-ssl-control multiple times has no extra effect.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] Disable it again with --no-ftp-ssl-control.
[src:curl-http-tool/manpage-p02] (HTTP) When used, this option makes all data specified with --data, --data-binary or --data-urlencode to be used in an HTTP GET request instead of the POST request that otherwise would be used. curl appends the provided data to the URL as a query string.
